WEBVTT

00:00.994 --> 00:04.118
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:04.699 --> 00:18.377
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization, using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:19.118 --> 00:26.668
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:26.708 --> 00:27.890
Today,

00:27.970 --> 00:35.978
We invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:39.582 --> 00:40.643
Peace be with you, friends.

00:40.663 --> 00:43.546
For this Sunday, I want to focus on our second reading.

00:43.626 --> 00:45.147
One that I don't preach on that often.

00:45.228 --> 00:48.611
It's an excerpt from Paul's second letter to Timothy.

00:49.091 --> 00:53.776
Those two great letters of Timothy we have are fascinating from a lot of perspectives.

00:54.257 --> 00:55.538
But it's Paul kind of

00:55.938 --> 01:01.847
giving fatherly advice in many ways to this young disciple of his, this convert Timothy.

01:02.649 --> 01:09.079
But the section today that's our second reading is really interesting because Paul's doing something that he does from time to time.

01:09.680 --> 01:20.237
He tends to make these elaborate theological arguments, but occasionally he'll kind of cut to the chase and he'll say in very pithy language what it's all about.

01:20.818 --> 01:21.739
So listen to this now.

01:21.779 --> 01:23.602
This is how the second reading commences.

01:24.386 --> 01:25.948
Beloved, he's addressing Timothy.

01:26.869 --> 01:33.356
Remember Jesus Christ raised from the dead, a descendant of David.

01:34.638 --> 01:36.400
Such is my gospel.

01:38.342 --> 01:42.186
Interestingly, Paul preaches the gospel, right?

01:42.206 --> 01:44.629
He's an evangelist, an evangelizer.

01:45.670 --> 01:46.891
But what's the gospel?

01:46.971 --> 01:49.234
That's a word we throw around a lot.

01:49.634 --> 01:54.219
There's gospel music, gospel preaching, there's gospel inspiration.

01:54.280 --> 01:56.762
He's a gospel inspired guy.

01:56.803 --> 01:59.806
What is the gospel?

01:59.826 --> 02:05.513
I remember many, many years ago, it was a good friend of my Chicago priest who kind of prided himself.

02:05.553 --> 02:10.939
He'd always say, I preach the gospel or we got to bring the people back to the gospel.

02:11.500 --> 02:15.765
So one day I said to him, what do you mean exactly when you say the gospel?

02:15.845 --> 02:16.626
And he said,

02:17.122 --> 02:20.706
What's whoever you do to the least of my brothers that you do unto me."

02:22.388 --> 02:28.675
So by the gospel, he meant Jesus' great ethical teaching to love, especially the poor and the marginalized.

02:28.695 --> 02:32.039
And he indeed was a man of great commitment to social justice.

02:32.079 --> 02:34.822
So that's what he meant by the gospel.

02:36.764 --> 02:38.045
But that's not the gospel.

02:39.006 --> 02:42.290
That's an ethical implication of the gospel.

02:43.554 --> 02:48.042
This is again, many years ago, I was in a Protestant Catholic dialogue.

02:48.543 --> 02:57.058
And the challenge given to us by the moderator who was a Protestant was I want each one around the table to say, what's the gospel?

02:58.220 --> 03:06.134
So my Protestant interlocutors, most of them did a version of the gospel is justification by grace to faith.

03:07.136 --> 03:08.178
That's the good news.

03:08.258 --> 03:13.766
You know, the great message of Romans and Galatians, justification by grace through faith.

03:15.408 --> 03:18.632
Well, that indeed is Luther's interpretation of Paul.

03:18.652 --> 03:27.945
And whatever you say about the relationship between faith and works and all that, may I suggest that's not the gospel.

03:28.886 --> 03:33.373
That's a doctrinal implication of the gospel.

03:34.734 --> 03:37.298
Now, I'm saying this because of this passage

03:37.378 --> 03:40.921
Listen to Paul, the first great evangelizer.

03:41.142 --> 03:42.283
Should nobody's talking about.

03:43.984 --> 03:50.531
Remember Jesus Christ raised from the dead at the center of David.

03:51.532 --> 03:54.494
Such is my gospel.

03:55.916 --> 03:56.997
What's the gospel, everybody?

03:58.198 --> 03:58.778
It's Jesus.

04:00.460 --> 04:04.844
And that's the answer, by the way, I gave around the table that day when they said, well, what's the gospel?

04:04.924 --> 04:06.706
I said, Jesus Christ.

04:07.842 --> 04:08.903
He's the good news.

04:09.984 --> 04:11.466
He's the glad tidings.

04:12.207 --> 04:16.511
Jesus himself, mind you, I said it before, but it bears repeating.

04:17.052 --> 04:19.655
Christianity is not a philosophy.

04:20.736 --> 04:22.117
It's not a set of ideas.

04:22.938 --> 04:25.401
It's not a noble spiritual path.

04:25.481 --> 04:27.083
It's not a spirituality.

04:28.624 --> 04:31.227
It might be all those things by a kind of implication.

04:32.849 --> 04:37.554
Christianity is a relationship to Jesus.

04:37.986 --> 04:39.668
It's about Him.

04:39.728 --> 04:42.051
It's about Him.

04:42.071 --> 04:46.137
Not primarily His moral teachings, all that's great.

04:46.217 --> 04:47.919
And it follows from Him.

04:47.939 --> 04:51.784
But the gospel is Jesus.

04:52.264 --> 04:59.634
Notice in the early centuries, the church did battle with the ancient heresy, pernicious as all get out.

05:00.002 --> 05:12.097
the ancient heresy of Gnosticism, which is precisely a tendency to turn away from the particular Jesus and to turn him into a turned Christianity into a kind of philosophical program.

05:12.938 --> 05:16.822
No, no, said the church up and down the ages until today.

05:16.862 --> 05:21.167
The gospel is Jesus in person.

05:21.388 --> 05:22.449
He's the good news.

05:23.170 --> 05:25.453
Now, but look what Paul specifies.

05:25.473 --> 05:26.974
They're both really interesting, I think.

05:27.996 --> 05:29.938
Remember Jesus Christ,

05:30.402 --> 05:31.584
And of course, there it is.

05:32.626 --> 05:35.711
Yeshua, He would have been thinking in His Hebrew mind.

05:35.731 --> 05:37.915
Yeshua, Mashiach.

05:37.935 --> 05:42.483
And then in His Greek that becomes Jesus Christos, Jesus Christ.

05:42.523 --> 05:51.179
It just means Jesus the anointed one who is raised from the dead and a descendant of David.

05:52.160 --> 05:53.042
Now can I suggest

05:53.218 --> 05:55.501
It's that second one, my strike he was peculiar.

05:56.222 --> 06:00.547
As Paul is talking about Jesus, well, all right, raised from the dead, I get that, that's pretty extraordinary.

06:01.108 --> 06:05.994
But why would he put such a stress on the fact that he's a descendant of David?

06:06.855 --> 06:16.507
I mean, if you're talking about the importance of a given human being, which is, well, let me tell you about this guy, he's the descendant of this great, great, great, great, great, great, great, great grandfather way, way back when.

06:17.108 --> 06:21.874
I mean, you say, yeah, that's true, I guess, but why is that interesting?

06:22.242 --> 06:30.372
Paul thought it was extremely interesting and important that Yeshua Mashiach is a descendant of David, no way.

06:31.894 --> 06:35.119
David the king, he's the paradigmatic king.

06:35.179 --> 06:36.701
He's the greatest king of Israel.

06:36.781 --> 06:45.011
He's the one who, at least in the Old Testament context, is providing the best kind of leadership for God's holy people.

06:45.352 --> 06:46.994
Now watch what David the king does.

06:47.875 --> 06:50.258
David the king unites the triumphs.

06:50.722 --> 06:54.867
So the 12 tribes of Israel, Israel is meant to be a united nation.

06:54.908 --> 07:01.957
And as such, it would gather in all the nations of the world by the very quality and integrity of its praise and its ethical behavior.

07:02.357 --> 07:04.320
A united Israel would gather the world.

07:05.161 --> 07:06.022
What did sin do?

07:06.223 --> 07:09.767
Remember the devil's name is the scatterer, Haudiavelos, he scatters.

07:10.148 --> 07:12.050
So the tribes are scattered by sin.

07:13.793 --> 07:14.634
What did David do?

07:14.694 --> 07:17.938
His first great act is to draw the tribes

07:18.274 --> 07:25.426
And if I remember they say, this is the bone of our bone and flesh of our flesh, it's a kind of mystical body of David, almost his form.

07:26.568 --> 07:27.690
So he gathers the tribes.

07:28.291 --> 07:32.137
Secondly, he established Jerusalem as the great capital city.

07:32.257 --> 07:33.840
And to that city, what did he do?

07:34.421 --> 07:39.148
He brought the Ark of the Covenant, dancing with reckless abandon before it.

07:40.130 --> 07:44.978
The Ark that contained the remains of the Ten Commandments and the staff of Aaron,

07:45.698 --> 07:47.901
It was the sign of God's presence among his people.

07:48.462 --> 07:52.027
It was the focal point of the worship of Israel.

07:52.768 --> 07:57.834
And from that ark eventually grew the temple as a place to house the ark.

07:59.016 --> 08:03.722
David establishes, if you want, the right praise in Israel.

08:04.684 --> 08:15.218
And then he becomes king over the 12 tribes and then begins to establish a kind of empire, even asserting Israelite influence over the other nations.

08:16.834 --> 08:21.296
Now, greatest king, yeah, but perfect king?

08:21.337 --> 08:24.854
Totally fulfilling God's desire?

08:25.216 --> 08:25.618
No, no.

08:26.306 --> 08:30.390
We know David's flaws, especially with regard to Bathsheba and Uriah.

08:30.410 --> 08:34.254
He's an adulterer and a murderer, so David is a compromise figure.

08:34.714 --> 08:40.760
More to it, his son Solomon builds a great temple, but the temple becomes corrupt almost automatically.

08:40.800 --> 08:42.842
The prophets rail against it.

08:43.303 --> 08:54.994
Yes, David knitted the nation together, but under the leadership of his son, that the nation splits apart and then descends into bickering and rivalry.

08:55.938 --> 08:57.701
David's empire is lost.

08:58.322 --> 09:06.216
And in fact, the enemies of Israel come at Israel, Assyria, then Babylon, then Persia, then Greece, and then Rome.

09:07.158 --> 09:12.548
So, yeah, David's the great king, but he didn't accomplish everything God wanted.

09:14.331 --> 09:16.434
And so, Israel begins to long.

09:16.474 --> 09:20.722
Now, mind you, this man talking here, Paul, he was Sha'ul.

09:20.834 --> 09:23.257
He was a rabbi studying under Gamaliel.

09:23.317 --> 09:26.081
He knew everything I've just been talking about.

09:26.561 --> 09:28.884
So he knew the longing of Israel, for what?

09:29.905 --> 09:31.968
For a descendant of David.

09:33.250 --> 09:35.452
I don't just mean in the physical sense, it is that.

09:35.913 --> 09:40.819
But I mean someone who would embody the fullness of what David's supposed to be.

09:42.381 --> 09:45.004
They called this figure the Mashiach.

09:46.026 --> 09:49.490
The Mashiach, because David was anointed, remember, by Samuel?

09:49.986 --> 09:56.135
And so this anointed figure, this new David would fulfill all the promises made to Israel.

09:56.836 --> 09:57.617
Okay, okay.

09:58.278 --> 10:03.065
Now, look at the first thing that Paul says when he says, Jesus Christ is the gospel.

10:03.746 --> 10:06.290
Jesus Christ raised from the dead.

10:07.211 --> 10:09.234
See, think of Rabbi Sha'ul Malm.

10:09.794 --> 10:12.979
young guy full of passion for the traditions of his people.

10:13.580 --> 10:20.290
And he hears about this nascent Christian movement, who's claiming that a crucified man is the Mashiach of Israel.

10:20.330 --> 10:22.574
He's joking, says young Sha'wul.

10:22.594 --> 10:23.275
No way.

10:23.856 --> 10:26.600
No way that the Messiah is supposed to gather the tribes.

10:26.620 --> 10:28.443
He's supposed to draw in the nations.

10:28.463 --> 10:30.947
He's supposed to reign as the king of the world.

10:31.288 --> 10:33.331
What do you mean someone crucified by the Romans?

10:33.791 --> 10:35.474
Is the Mashiach, are you crazy?

10:36.002 --> 10:38.366
And that's why he persecutes the church.

10:38.806 --> 10:42.652
That's why he went with a ferocious abandon.

10:42.672 --> 10:43.673
He goes after the church.

10:46.638 --> 10:47.499
And then he saw him.

10:50.323 --> 10:52.086
I don't know any other way to explain it.

10:52.727 --> 10:53.829
And it's what Paul tells us.

10:54.690 --> 10:55.872
He saw him.

10:56.533 --> 10:57.835
He didn't come to a new idea.

10:57.875 --> 10:59.257
He didn't come to a new philosophy.

10:59.277 --> 11:01.480
He didn't figure something out about his ethical life.

11:02.001 --> 11:02.321
No, no.

11:02.922 --> 11:05.426
On the road to Damascus, he saw

11:06.050 --> 11:09.675
Him, Jesus of Nazareth.

11:10.456 --> 11:14.060
Sha'ul, Sha'ul, why are you persecuting me?

11:14.400 --> 11:15.982
Who are you, sir, that I might know?

11:16.423 --> 11:19.627
I am Jesus, Yeshua, whom you are persecuting.

11:21.129 --> 11:24.333
And Sha'ul becomes the Apostle Paul.

11:24.994 --> 11:26.095
And what did he figure out?

11:26.776 --> 11:28.778
Ah, ah, now I get it.

11:30.481 --> 11:32.323
He is the new David.

11:33.504 --> 11:34.866
The risen Christ

11:35.234 --> 11:39.380
is the Lord whose purpose is to gather in the nations of the world.

11:39.740 --> 11:40.962
Now look at Paul's mission.

11:41.382 --> 11:42.884
Now look at Paul's mission.

11:43.245 --> 11:44.306
That's what he was doing.

11:44.707 --> 11:50.034
In the name of Yeshua Mashiach, Yeza's Christos, he was drawing in the nations.

11:51.796 --> 11:54.340
Yes, this risen Christ cleansed the temple.

11:54.440 --> 11:54.720
How?

11:55.181 --> 11:57.224
By becoming himself the new temple.

11:58.205 --> 12:01.810
Jesus great sacrifice on the cross offered to the Father.

12:03.138 --> 12:06.162
becomes the fullness of temple worship.

12:06.863 --> 12:09.447
He himself is the right praise of Israel.

12:12.010 --> 12:13.773
Dealing with the enemies of the nation.

12:13.933 --> 12:17.098
Yeah, David started, but David didn't complete that process.

12:18.620 --> 12:25.970
Ah, but now Paul sees Jesus on the cross of his took on all the enemies

12:26.370 --> 12:34.440
of Israel, all the enemies of God, hatred and violence and persecution and aggression and death itself, all of it, all of it.

12:34.860 --> 12:41.929
And through the resurrection, he shows God's victory over all the enemies of Israel.

12:43.050 --> 12:43.931
Ah, okay.

12:45.533 --> 12:55.986
My gospel, my good news is him, Jesus Christ, risen from the dead and the descendant of David.

12:56.546 --> 12:59.393
the one who fulfills the great promise of David.

13:00.055 --> 13:02.862
Now, just a couple of things in the minute I got left.

13:04.887 --> 13:11.583
Such is my gospel, listen, for which I am suffering, even to the point of chains like a criminal.

13:13.207 --> 13:14.450
Do you see now why?

13:15.042 --> 13:23.337
If he were preaching some bland spiritual message, like a thing, something you buy in a bookstore, you know, in Santa Barbara, I mean, no one throw them in prison.

13:23.737 --> 13:24.539
Why would they bother?

13:24.579 --> 13:28.847
It's just some, some, you know, harmless spiritual meditation.

13:30.089 --> 13:33.655
No, what Paul was saying was Jesus is the Lord.

13:34.236 --> 13:35.017
He's the king.

13:35.078 --> 13:36.360
It's not Caesar.

13:36.400 --> 13:39.826
That's why the advocates of Caesar weren't too happy with them.

13:40.034 --> 13:50.611
But the thing now, up and down the ages, whenever we say, well, money is king, power is king, sex and pleasure are king, my country is king, this president, none of it's king.

13:50.631 --> 13:53.856
If Jesus is who he says he is, he's the Lord.

13:54.437 --> 13:59.385
So of course, of course, when you preach this gospel, you will get in trouble.

14:00.046 --> 14:01.889
But here's the great good news.

14:03.111 --> 14:06.076
But the Word of God is not chained.

14:06.957 --> 14:07.378
Right.

14:07.842 --> 14:09.964
They can chain the bearers of the Word.

14:09.984 --> 14:12.727
And they did from Paul all the way to Maximilian Colby.

14:13.068 --> 14:17.052
You can chain up the bearers of the Word, but you can't chain the Word.

14:17.353 --> 14:17.853
You know why?

14:18.194 --> 14:19.475
Because that's the gospel.

14:20.256 --> 14:21.237
That's the gospel.

14:21.697 --> 14:26.683
This declaration of Jesus, a descendant of David raised from the dead.

14:27.364 --> 14:32.029
Everybody, everything else in our Catholic lives is a footnote to that.

14:32.990 --> 14:34.972
This is the heart of the matter.

14:35.893 --> 14:36.594
And God bless you.

14:40.546 --> 14:44.160
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

14:44.562 --> 14:49.682
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.

